Issues.Body:
Up until this point, all static attribute values (things like `title` and `id`)
defined within the `host` are of a Component/Directive definition were
generated into a `def.attributes` array and then processed at runtime.
This design decision does not lend itself well to tree-shaking and is
inconsistent with other static values such as styles and classes.

This fix ensures that all static attribute values (attributes, classes,
and styles) that exist within a host definition for components and
directives are all assigned via the `elementHostAttrs` instruction.

```ts
// before
defineDirective({
  ...
  attributes: ['title', 'my title']
  ...
})

//now
defineDirective({
  ...
  hostBindings: function() {
    if (create) {
      elementHostAttrs(..., ['title', 'my-title']);
    }
    ...
  }
  ...
})
```

# üêû bug report

### Description

`ngtsc` fails to compile an application using ng-bootstrap because i18n messages have weird identifiers generated by `ngcc`.

For example, in `./node_modules/@ng-bootstrap/ng-bootstrap/fesm5/ng-bootstrap.js` after running `ngcc`:
```
const MSG_EXTERNAL_ngb.alert.close$$FESM5_NG_BOOTSTRAP_JS__15 = goog.getMsg("Close");
```
Note the dots in the name of the constant.

That produces after `ng build --aot` in an Ivy app:

```
ERROR in ./node_modules/@ng-bootstrap/ng-bootstrap/fesm5/ng-bootstrap.js 71:22
Module parse failed: Unexpected token (71:22)
You may need an appropriate loader to handle this file type.
| const _c13 = ["alert-dismissible"];
| const _c14 = ["type", "button", 1, "close", 3, "click"];
> const MSG_EXTERNAL_ngb.alert.close$$FESM5_NG_BOOTSTRAP_JS__15 = goog.getMsg("Close");
| const _c16 = ["aria-label", MSG_EXTERNAL_ngb.alert.close$$FESM5_NG_BOOTSTRAP_JS__15];
| const _c17 = ["aria-hidden", "true"];
```

### Is this a regression?

No it has been present for a while

